  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US) first required financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Limited initial scope and enforcement mechanisms\n\n2. International Developments\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards and recommendations\n- Encouraged global cooperation against money laundering\n\n3. Major Legislative Milestones\n- 1990s: Enhanced reporting requirements\n- 2001 USA PATRIOT Act dramatically expanded anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Increased information sharing between financial institutions and law enforcement\n\n4. Modern Approaches\n- Comprehensive Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n- Expanded definition of financial institutions\n\n5. Emerging Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n- Machine learning and AI-assisted detection\n- Focus on beneficial ownership transparency\n\n6. Recent Developments\n- Increased emphasis on combating terrorist financing\n- More sophisticated risk-based compliance approaches\n- Regulatory technology (RegTech) solutions\n\nThe legislative landscape continues to evolve with technological and criminal innovations.",
